reviews.text:
A fantastic trek! I've seen crystal clear natural pools like this in lots of other countries, but the amazing, beautiful, and weird rock formations still make this one special. And there are good places to swim in the beautiful water too (not right at the edge of the falls - see below).

The trail starts from a hundred meters or so outside the gate of the waterfall viewpoint. I was told that I still needed to buy a 50rs entry ticket for the trek (separate from the viewpoint ticket), though no one checked my ticket at the trailhead. It's only for people who are in reasonably good physical shape. The trail has three sections - an easy stroll along a small road along the top of the plateau, a steep and rigorous trail down a forested slope (and back up again later), and then a barely-marked route along the riverbed to the top of the falls. On that last section there are white arrows painted in some places to show you the recommended way, but I sometimes couldn't find them, and had to find my own way a couple times (very carefully - there are plenty of places to fall to your death, including lots of holes in the rock that are much, much deeper than you would expect). From the bottom of the forested slope there are also red arrows pointing the way upstream to another mini-waterfall.

The best place to swim is in a huge, swimming-pool sized pool of clear water just before you start to see the edge of the waterfall (it should be safe as long as the water isn't high enough to be rushing out from the downstream end, though you do need good swimming skills, as it's quite deep - and cold).
More trekking. Little tuff, not recommended in the rainy season.  Chilled water be careful before diving into the pool.

Umngot River is considered one of the most beautiful and pristine rivers in India, and it's no surprise that it's become a popular tourist destination.

Visitors to Umngot River are treated to breathtaking views of crystal-clear waters that reflect the lush greenery and towering cliffs that surround it. The river is also known for its unique feature of changing colors, which is a result of the varying depths of the water and the sunlight that hits it at different angles throughout the day.

Tourists can enjoy a variety of activities on the river, such as boating, fishing, and swimming. The boat rides, in particular, are a must-do activity, where visitors can float along the tranquil waters and take in the stunning scenery around them.

One thing to note is that Umngot River is located in a remote area, and it may take some effort to get there. However, the journey is definitely worth it, as the river is truly a hidden gem that offers a peaceful escape from the hustle and bustle of city life.

Overall, if you're looking for a unique and unforgettable experience in India, a visit to Umngot River should definitely be on your bucket list.

The small border town Dawki of Meghalaya is popular for its famous Umngot river and a beautiful suspension bridge. It is a major tourist destination in Meghalaya. The water of Umngot river is so clear that the boats floating on it, look as if they are on a crystal glass surface. Dawki lies between India and Bangladesh and is the trade hub between the two countries. People come to this place to enjoy a boat ride in the Umngot river and view of the surrounding greenery. Charge for boat riding is Rs. 800/- per boat.

reviews.text:
On arrival, visitors are left awestruck by the scenic beauty of the area: beautiful green meadows stretching out far and wide, with the woods tucked away in a corner. the forest itself is divided into three sections, of which only the first and the second section can be visited. Guides are compulsory; however, you can sign up for a 20- to 30-minute half trek or a 40- to 60-minute full trek.
Guide Fees - 300 Rs. Ticket & Parking Another 100Rs.

At the entrance to the Mawphlang Sacred Forest is the first group of monoliths: three standing stones and one seated stone. this is where village elders seek permission from the deity to carry out the sacrificial ritual inside the for- est. it was believed that if a leopard appeared, it was an auspicious sign and the ritual could be conducted as planned. however, if a snake appeared, it was considered inauspicious and the ritual would be abandoned. the entrance to the forest resembles a â€˜green tunnelâ€™, all naturally formed by the branches of the trees. inside the forest, the only audible sounds are the melodious calls of songbirds, the hum of crickets, the buzz of bees and dragonflies and occasionally the gurgling of forest streams. The forest floor is carpeted with humus, which has accumulated here for centuries, so be cautious of your step, especially where the trail grows narrow.

Beautiful Forest. The property is managed and curated by the local villagers. The forest is a sacred space for them and they treat it with utmost respect. The trip is guided by locals and full snippets about the cultural heritage. There are decent restrooms near the parking lot and a snack place at the entrance. The trip to the center of the forest and back takes about an hour, I would recommend being hydrated and fresh for it.

reviews.text:
This was a little farther from double root bridge, around 40 min hike. I saw beautiful blue and clean streams amidst the jungle which kept me motivated. For the longest there was no sign of the waterfall but thanks to a couple of strangers on the way who told me to continue. And man was it worth it! It was the most beautiful sight!! From the top one can just see the blue of water but go down and that's where the rainbow is visible from. It's very subtle but beautiful. Such pristine surroundings. It's breathtaking! Photos definitely don't do justice to the place!!!.
There is a maggi shop also to relax and eat and soak in the view.
You might feel tired at the end of the double root but this will absolutely refresh you. One can also take a dip in the water! So do do go!!
Also, would advise to get a hiking stick at the entrance. It comes in very handy while going back and climbing all the stairs.

It's a beautiful falls with eye catching green water that you will find worth the trek. This takes about 1-1.5 hrs of forest trail trekking to reach rainbow falls from double decker root bridge. It's tougher route than the double decker one as you don't have proper steps, it's mostly stone setup as steps and it's highs and lows throughout the route. You don't have to pack too many water bottles with you as it might be heavy to carry, also there are many shops on the way you can get a bottle or juice as needed. Absolutely unnecessary to pack for the entire trek. Carry a glucose pack each, it was life saver for us. Everytime you are tired, have a spoon or two it gives instant energy and you will magically have strength to cope for next 20-30 mins. There was a shop in the final location where we had some Maggie and snacks. I suggest you carry very minimal snacks like energy bars and some biscuits just in case you are hungry before reaching the place. There is restrooms available as well in some places. It was pretty manageable for us. It took us 1 to reach rainbow falls from double decker root bridge and return took us little less than an hour to return to double decker root bridge. From double decker root bridge to starting point of the trek took us 1.5 hrs and it was super difficult as it was very steep uphill. Also our guide said we were quite fast unlike other tourists. So please don't expect everyone to complete at this speed.

Guides are all over the place when you start the trek. Remember you don't need this. You need to pay 600 till double decker root bridge or 1000 till rainbow falls. The only confusion you will have is in the start where the steps are going up and one goes down on your left. Choose the steps that goes down on your left (this will take you to double decker) . Everything from there is pretty straight forward. There is no room to get lost whatsoever guide tells you. We hired guide because of the initial confusion. However I highly recommend you taking a guide if you have kids or heavy bags. Though they aren't helpful to guide you through the route, they can carry your bags and take pictures for you, they also carried kids. I'm sure that's quite useful that way. Regarding the sticks that people rent in the start of the trek, it's totally useless unless you have knee pain or elderly person who needs support to walk. Stick will also add weight and will be a hindrance to your speed it's much easier without stick. You always have rails to hold on to or you can sit on steps as you need to rest. Staying hydrated and going in steady pace is the key to finish the trek.
